===Etymology===
First attested in the late 14th century. From {{inh|en|enm|accusacion}}, borrowed from {{bor|en|fro|acusacion}} (French {{m|fr|accusation}}), from {{der|en|la|accūsātiō||accusation, indictment}}, from {{m|la|accūsō||blame, accuse}}. More at {{m|en|accuse}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˌæk.jʊ.ˈzeɪ.ʃən/|/ˌæk.jə.ˈzeɪ.ʃən/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-accusation.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|eɪʃən}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# The act of [[accusing]].
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Shakespeare|title=Henry VIII, III-i|passage=We come not by the way of '''accusation''' / To taint that honour every good tongue blesses.}}
# {{lb|en|legal}} A [[formal]] [[charge]] brought against a person in a [[court of law]].
#* Bible, Matthew 27:37
#*: [They] set up over his head his '''accusation'''.
# An [[allegation]].

